<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910806-0146</DOCNO><DOCID>910806-0146.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   XL/Datacomp   To Be Acquired   For $150 Million   ----   By Karen Blumenthal   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   STK XLDC</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)OTHER SPECIALTY RETAILERS OF LIMITED PRODUCT LINES (OTS)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>COLORADO (CO)ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOUISVILLE, Colo. -- Storage Technology Corp., signalingits plan to roll out products for the minicomputer market,said it agreed to acquire XL/Datacomp Inc. for stock valuedat about $150 million.   Under the agreement, Storage Technology, a maker ofdata-storage products primarily for mainframe computers,would issue 0.2675 share for each share of XL/Datacomp, adistributor of International Business Machines Corp.minicomputer systems and support services.</LP><TEXT>   Storage Technology said the purchase would give it accessto a sales force familiar with reaching users of smallercomputers, as well as a distributor for its IBM-compatibleproducts. Storage Technology's hottest seller is itsautomated cartridge system, a jukebox-like machine thatallows mainframe computers to retrieve quickly as many as6,000 cartridge tapes of data. The company is expected tointroduce a cartridge system for the so-called midrangemarket, as well as other storage products for minicomputersystems.   News of the definitive agreement, which valuesXL/Datacomp's shares at about $12.50 each, sent XL/Datacomp'sstock up $1.375 to $11.875 yesterday in nationalover-the-counter trading, on heavy volume of 2.5 millionshares. Storage Technology's stock, however, was quoted at$47.125 in late New York Stock Exchange trading, down $2.875from Friday's close.   Storage Technology, which has about 36 million sharesoutstanding currently, said the transaction would be treatedas a pooling-of-interests transaction and must be approved byXL/Datacomp's shareholders. The companies said that holdersof 27% of XL/Datacomp's stock have agreed to vote for themerger. XL/Datacomp has 12 million shares outstanding.   For the nine months ended June 30, XL/Datacomp, based inHinsdale, Ill., had a net loss of $3.4 million, or 28 cents ashare, including a $6.5 million loss from discontinuedoperations and a $3.1 million gain from continuingoperations. Revenue was $275.7 million, down 16% from theyear-earlier period, which the company attributed to a delayin delivery schedules and the weak economy.   Storage Technology had net income of $34.6 million, or 98cents a share, on revenue of $578.1 milion for the six monthsended June 28.</TEXT></DOC>